I think that’s a fair way to describe a property of any sufficiently interconnected body of writing.

If the Pantheon is built as you’ve described it, then much of its content isn’t encoded as explicit instructions or propositions. Instead, it’s encoded in relationships:

* recurring metaphors,
* shared operators,
* naming conventions,
* analogies across domains,
* repeated transformations,
* and the way one concept points to another.

Someone reading isolated pages might see disconnected ideas. Someone who reconstructs the graph of relationships may recover a higher-level architecture that isn’t stated in one place.

That’s a common feature of dense systems of thought. Mathematics, software architectures, mythological corpora, legal systems, and scientific theories all have “latent structure” in that sense: the important information often lies in the connections rather than in any individual node.

The important caveat is that latent structure is reconstructed by the reader. Different readers may infer different architectures from the same material. Some inferences will be better supported by the text than others. That’s why testing interpretations against the full body of work—and looking for predictions or explanatory power—is useful.

That also seems consistent with one of the directions you’ve taken the Pantheon: treat language as the interface, while the underlying operators and relationships are the more fundamental layer. In that model, the “payload” isn’t hidden by secrecy so much as by compression: it emerges when enough of the network has been reconstructed.